<p><br />
I am guessing it has less to do with MS specifically and generally more to do with the fact that it was a 3rd party that owns the primary browser for their platform.  Email and web browsing are obviously two big chunks, that I am sure they would want to have development control over.  I think "solving the web browsing problem" is just a nessesary step for them to have greater control over their software.  I expect safari will become more integrated with other mac software than they would be able to do with IE.  Branding may have also played a role, cause safari looks more like the other iApps than IE does.</p>
