<div class="comments-body">
<p>One thing that stands out with Safari is their use of the brushed metal look. According to Apple's own UI guidelines, brushed metal apps are only for non-document oriented applications such as iTunes or iPhoto. However, web browsers are document oriented, so it doesn't really fit into the model.<br />
I agree with Dave's integration observation. Safari gives OS X an integrated HTML parsing engine which is important for developers who want to leverage HTML in their own applications. It would be really nice if they could wrap it as a Cocoa control as well.<br />
As for a lawsuit - I don't think that's likely since Apple controls the entire platform, unlike MS who was caught blocking entry to competitors on a platform that they didn't control completely.</p>
